body_text.text:
The steps in the mechanistic model developed here for infection of an arthropod vector are shown in Fig. 1
. The thermodynamic component of the model here focuses on arbovirus binding to the microvillae surface (the so-called brush borders) of the arthropod midgut epithelial cell which is the first step in infection of the arthropod (Forrester et al., 2012, Franz et al., 2015) and involves specific interactions between a receptor molecule (Cr) on the brush border surface and a (glyco)protein (GP) on the arbovirus coat. In the case of BTV for example, the Cr may be a sialic acid (SA) on the arthropod midgut epithelial cell surface (Zhang et al., 2010). Here three thermodynamic GP/Cr binding scenarios, namely enthalpy-driven (Fei et al., 2015), entropy-driven (Casasnovas and Springer, 1995) and entropy-assisted (Caro et al., 2017) are considered in terms of their impact in modulating the effect of temperature on the strength of virus binding to a midgut cell as represented by Ka. In enthalpy-driven binding, it is the large negative ΔHa_virus term in Equation 1 that dominates in maximizing Ka and overcoming an unfavorable negative ΔSa_virus term (see Table 2
), while in entropy-driven binding it is the large positive ΔSa_virus term that overcomes an unfavorable positive ΔHa_virus term. In entropy-assisted binding a small positive ΔSa_virus term adds to a small negative ΔHa_virus term in maximizing Ka (Table 2). The magnitude of Ka together with the virus dose (∼Vfree) in the midgut dictate the number (C.VT) of arthropod midgut cells with bound virus at a given temperature (Gale, 2018) according to Equation 5 and Equation 6. In addition to the strength of the binding of GP to Cr as represented by the thermodynamic dissociation constant, Kd_receptor (Xiong et al., 2013), two other factors affect Ka, namely the number, n, of GP/Cr contacts made on binding of the virus to a cell and the unknown entropy term ΔSa_immob (see above). The kinetic component as represented by pcompleteT in Equation 2 is the probability of spread of infectivity through the arthropod to its salivary glands at a given temperature once virus in the initial challenge dose in the ingested blood-meal has bound to a midgut cell brush border. This represents the rate of virus replication and has to be completed within the lifetime of the arthropod so that it can infect another vertebrate host through feeding before it dies. In this respect, the probability pcompleteT has an implicit time dimension. The thermodynamic output, C.VT, and kinetic output, pcompleteT, are linked through the standard “dose-response” relationship in Equation 7 to give the transmission efficiency (vector competence) at temperature T as represented by ptransmissionT.
